This remarkable parallelism cannot, in my judgment, be ac- counted for, except on the supposition that the passage preceding the direct citation from the Hortensius is also based upon this same dialogue.

Still another echo of this Ciceronian treatise I am disposed to find, although, unlike the previous instance, my suspicion does not admit of positive proof, in the following parallel with a fragment preserved by Augustinus, de trinit. c. XIV 9:

Si nobis cum ex hac vita emigraveri- Dial. c. 41 7 ff. quod si inveniretur ali-

mus in beatorum insulis inmortale aevum ut fabulae ferunt degere licet, quid opus esset eloquentia cum iudicia nulla fierent. . . nee’iustitia cum esset nihil quod appeterentur alieni nec temperantia quae regeret

qua civitas in qua nemo peccaret, supervacuus esset inter innocentes orator . . . quid voluntariis accusati- onibus (sc. opus est) cum tam raro et tam parce peccetur 12 11 felix illud . . . aureum saeculum et ora-

eas quae nullae essent libidines, ne prudentia quidem egeremus nullo delecto proposito bonorum et ma- lorum.
